## Concept Overview
TCP's congestion control operates at the transport layer, managing the entire connection's throughput regardless of how many application-layer streams (HTTP/2) are multiplexed over it.

## Implementation Details
- TCP uses algorithms like Reno, CUBIC, or BBR to adjust cwnd based on packet loss/RTT
- HTTP/2 multiplexes multiple streams over a single TCP connection
- All streams share the same congestion window and experience identical throttling

## Common Pitfalls
- Assuming per-stream bandwidth allocation
- Ignoring that packet loss affects all streams simultaneously
- Not considering TCP head-of-line blocking despite HTTP/2 stream multiplexing

## Code Example
```go
// HTTP/2 client configuration
client := &http.Client{
    Transport: &http2.Transport{
        // Single TCP connection for all streams
        AllowHTTP: false,
    },
}
```
